@startuml
title SUID at exec — temporary identity change

actor "User alice\n(RUID 1000)" as alice
participant "Shell\nEUID 1000" as shell
participant "Kernel\nexecve()" as kernel
participant "passwd process\n-rwsr-xr-x root root" as proc
database "/etc/shadow\nowner root, mode 0600" as shadow

alice -> shell : run /usr/bin/passwd
shell -> kernel : execve("/usr/bin/passwd")
kernel -> kernel : SUID bit set?\nset EUID = file owner (root)
kernel -> proc : start with RUID 1000, EUID 0
proc -> shadow : write new password hash
note right of shadow
  Permitted because the
  check uses EUID (root),
  not RUID (alice).
end note
shadow --> proc : OK
proc --> shell : exit, back to EUID 1000
note over proc
  Risk: any flaw in a SUID-root
  binary runs with root rights.
  This is why SUID is the most
  dangerous of the base primitives.
end note
@enduml
